text: In 1997 , Mexico ' s total amount of foreign trade broke through 220 billion US dollars , which created a new historical record .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> Mexico <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: However , in reviewing Mexico ' s foreign trade situation this year , it might be appropriate to say that it is between joy and sorrow .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> Mexico <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> it <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: The joy lies in that the total amount of foreign trade still maintains a strong growth momentum , and has realized trade surpluses for the third year in a row , whereas the sorrow is that the amount of trade surplus has sharply reversed , and this year , a relatively large deficit may appear .
record: <extra_id_0>  <extra_id_1>

text: According to official journals published recently by Mexico ' s Treasury Department , in 1997 , foreign trade continues to grow at high speed , the total amount of imports and exports reached 220 . 178 billion US dollars , 18 . 85 % higher than that of the previous year , among which the amount of exports is 110 . 38 billion US dollars , imports were 109 . 798 billion US dollars , being 15 % and 22 . 7 % higher than that of 1996 respectively .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> Mexico <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> organization <extra_id_5> Mexico ' s Treasury Department <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: The trade surplus was 582 million US dollars .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: Foreign trade occupies a pivotal position in Mexico ' s economy .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> Mexico <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: At present , exports account for more than 30 % of its GDP , which is one of the primary economic growth forces .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> its <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: After the outbreak of Mexico ' s financial crisis in 1994 , Mexico ' s currency , the peso was greatly devalued , thus greatly strengthening Mexico ' s export competitiveness .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> Mexico <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> Mexico <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> Mexico <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: In the last several years , the government has been vigorously supporting exports , and exports grew rapidly .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> the government <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: In 1995 , the situation of successive foreign trade deficit reversed , and up to now , has maintained trade surpluses for three years in a row .
record: <extra_id_0>  <extra_id_1>

text: However , in the past three years , Mexico ' s foreign trade surplus showed a substantial degradation : 7 . 889 billion US dollars in 1995 , 6 . 424 billion US dollars in 1996 , and only 582 million US dollars last year .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> Mexico <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: Especially deserving to be pointed out is that , after the first monthly deficit in July last year , the rest of the year saw successive monthly deficits with the amounts of deficit almost doubling , roaring from 20 million US dollars in July to 722 million US dollars in December , reducing the 1997 annual accumulative trade surplus amount to a trivial number .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_0> geographical social political <extra_id_5> US <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: Local economic analysts felt that the trade deficit in the second half of last year was mainly due to an overly high import growth rate , which is even higher than that of exports .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> person <extra_id_5> Local economic analysts <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: In the second half of last year , the average growth rate of imports was 6 % to 7 % higher than that of exports .
record: <extra_id_0>  <extra_id_1>

text: Among import sectors , swift growth comes mainly from imports of consumer products and capital goods , 39 . 9 % and 38 . 2 % higher than that of 1996 respectively .
record: <extra_id_0> <extra_id_0> person <extra_id_5> consumer <extra_id_1> <extra_id_1>

text: The growth of imports of semi - finished products was up by 18 . 8 % .
record: <extra_id_0>  <extra_id_1>

text: Secondly , the overly high valuation of the peso is also an indispensable factor .
record: <extra_id_0>  <extra_id_1>

text: An overly high peso exchange rate stimulated imports , but hindered exports .
